    <name>Viking Lander 1</name>
    <type>Spacecraft</type>
    <naif_host_id>VL1</naif_host_id>
    <description>The Viking Landers, launched in 1976, were the first spacecraft to successfully operate on Mars for an extended period, continuing until 1982. Viking Lander 1 was later renamed the Thomas A. Mutch Memorial Station in honor of its team leader who died in an accident. Both landers were identical, equipped with a hexagonal prism design housing computers, instruments, and communication systems. They utilized radioisotope thermoelectric generators (RTGs) for power and included various scientific instruments for imaging, meteorology, seismology, elemental analysis, and biological experimentation. Notably, the seismometer on Viking Lander 1 failed to deploy, whereas Viking Lander 2's functioned correctly. The scientific investigations aimed to explore Mars' atmospheric and surface properties, search for organic compounds, and study its geology.</description>
  </Instrument_Host>
